We recommended and the management agreed that they require the Inventory Committee:

)To conduct an inventory of all PPE accounts once every year and COA must be invited as an observer;

)To observe the procedures prescribed under COA Circular No. 2020-006 pertaining to missing/non-existing property by identifying the officers/personnel who are accountable for these properties and demand the production of the same;

)The disposition procedures for non-existing/missing PPEs should be strictly implemented in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020.

d.)Request from COA an authority to derecognize the unaccountable missing PPE from the books of accounts after an investigation in accordance with Paragraph 8 of this Circular.

Recommendation
We recommended and the Management agreed to:
Submit an explanation or justification why rental cost of heavy equipment was included in the Program of Work and Detailed Estimates of the listed projects implemented by administration;
Submit the respective Driver’s Trip Tickets and the corresponding Monthly Reports of Fuel Consumption for each heavy equipment owned;
Moving forward, we recommended and the Management also agreed that the Municipal Development Council and Municipal Planning and Development Officer (MPDO) judiciously plan and evaluate the economic development projects to be implemented by the Municipality ensuring that the funds and resources of the government are allocated and utilized efficiently for the benefit of the constituents.

We recommended and the management agreed that:

The Municipal Assessor to provide a copy of an updated Assessment Roll to the Municipal Treasurer pursuant to Article 339 of the IRR of RA No. 7160 which states that the Municipal Assessor shall submit as assessment roll containing a list of all persons whose real properties have been newly assessed and the values of such properties to the Municipal Treasurer concerned on or before the 31st day of December each year;

The Municipal Treasurer to update the RPT Account Register/ Taxpayer’s index card based on the Assessment Roll and furnish the Municipal Accountant a duly certified list showing the names of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year;
The Municipal Accountant to draw a JEV to record the debit to RPT/SET Receivables and credit to Deferred RPT/ SET Income based on the certified list of due and collectible RPT for the year submitted by the Municipal Treasurer; and

 The Municipal Accountant to reconcile recordings involving RPT/ SET transactions and make necessary correcting/ adjusting entries.

15.8. 	We recommended that management submit a written explanation on the (a) discrepancy/ies in the obligations and utilization report vis-à-vis accomplishment report; 

(b) recovery and/or intervention programs not in line with the rationale of the declaration of the state of calamity. 

Also, submit complete documents to support the explanations and/or justifications.

15.9. 	Moving forward, we recommended that management: 

(a) prioritize the implementation of the PPAs identified during the year to ensure the readiness of the Municipality in case of calamity; 

(b) ensure that the recovery and/or intervention PPAs funded out of the 30% QRF are in line with the rationale of the declaration of state of calamity; and 

(c) ensure that the 5% LDRRM funds will be utilized in accordance with the established rules and regulations;

21.8. 	We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) issue directive requiring: 

(a) that the preparation of the contract/POs will be under the GSO functions and all the PRs will pass through the GSO for proper monitoring; 

(b) the GSO to ensure that the data/information on the PRs and POs are complete before it will be forwarded to the LCE for approval; 

(c) all the deliveries for the procurement of goods will pass through the GSO for acceptance; 

(d) the GSO to ensure that all the issuance of goods/items to the end-users will be covered by duly approved Requisition and Issuance Slip;

21.9. 	We further recommended that the LCE and the OIC-Municipal Accountant to ensure the propriety and completeness of the supporting documents before certifying and approving the disbursement vouchers.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive: 

To strengthen the internal control system of the Municipality by avoiding the assignment of incompatible functions to one individual and/or department;

To instruct the MEEO to ensure that a binding lease contract between the lessor and the lessee is prepared before authorizing the use/release of the heavy equipment from the motor pool services;

To require the in-charge of motor pool services to monitor the usage of the heavy equipment and submit monthly monitoring report to the GSO;

To require the MEEO to issue a billing statement to the lessee for the rental amount due;

To instruct the collectors to ensure that the rental payment by the lessee is supported with approved billing statement;

To stop the practice of using the collections to pay the approved DVs and enforce that all collections be turned over by the collectors intact within the prescribed period to the Liquidating Officer;

Open a separate bank account for the MEE; and

To require the Liquidating Officer and the OIC-Municipal Treasurer to deposit with the authorized depository bank all the collections turned-over to them within the prescribed period.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) and the Local Finance (Budget Officer, Accountant, and the Treasurer) explore for all possible solution to minimize the mandatory obligations with no cash back-up.
Moving forward, we recommend that the LCE and the Local Finance:
a. Consider the mandatory obligations with no cash back-up in the preparation of their annual budget;
c. Verify the status, existence, and validity of the obligations recorded in the financial statements;
d. Ensure that the incurrence of expenditures is within the total income realized during the year; and
e. Exercise diligence, prudence, and proper control in the disposition of government funds.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) issue a directive that:
(a) All the PRs will pass through the GSO for proper monitoring;
(b) the GSO ensure that the data/information on the PRs and POs are complete before forwarded to the LCE for approval;
(c) the acceptance of all delivered goods procured will pass through the GSO for approval; and
(d) the GSO ensure that all the issuance of goods/items to the end-users will be covered by duly approved Requisition and Issuance Slip;
We further recommended that the OIC-Municipal Accountant ensure the supporting documents' propriety and completeness before certifying and approving the disbursement vouchers.

We recommend that the Management:

To strictly comply with the provisions of RA 9184 in the procurement of drugs, medicines, reagents, supplies and equipment;
To stop granting cash advances to officers that are not bonded;
To grant the cash advance for the payment of professional fee of the RHU personnel through the authorized disbursing officer; and
To submit the cash advance disbursement vouchers and the liquidation reports to the audit team immediately.

